<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUN 94 / Wellcome Trust seeks move to venture capital
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Wellcome Trust, the UK's largest charitable trust, is seeking to
persuade the Charity Commission to approve a trustees' decision to invest
Pounds 100m in venture capital projects.
Permission of the Charity Commission is not legally required, but Wellcome
Trust would be uncomfortable in making a significant investment which
regulators might be unhappy about, said Sir Roger Gibbs, trust director. In
July 1987, Wellcome Trust secured legal permission to engage in a variety of
investment activities, including venture capital.
The move, which would place 2 per cent of the roughly Pounds 5.5bn of assets
into venture capital, could provide a fillip for the sector. It appears the
trust would like to invest in US-based venture capital projects. The process
might take up to three years.
Sir Roger said: 'We believe it imperative to protect the capital value of
our fund whilst at the same time generating a sizeable income for the
benefit of medical research.' He added that income from the trust's
investments was expected to generate more than Pounds 220m this year, more
than enough to meet commitments.
The average UK charity has a 'negligible' exposure to venture capital, while
the average UK pension scheme has less than 1 per cent of assets in the
sector, according to WM Company, a performance measurement service. However,
a handful of the UK's largest pension schemes, such as those of British Coal
and PosTel, have as much as 3 per cent of their assets in the sector and
have profited handsomely over the years.
Venture capital is considered more risky than investment in securities
although potential returns are higher. The projects are more speculative and
the investments are illiquid, depending on either a trade sale or a
flotation for investors to realise a gain.
The Charity Commission said on Friday that while it had no specific rules
barring venture capital investment, charities might invest only in areas set
out in their trust deeds. Venture capital is an unusual investment for a
charity because it is unlikely immediately to generate the cash most
charities require.
There is concern that the Charity Commission may view venture capital
investment as engaging in a trade or business, activities forbidden to
charities. However, investment advisers to Wellcome Trust believe the
charity has a strong case for venture capital investment. First, its
existing portfolio and 40 per cent stake in the Wellcome drug company give
it ample cashflow to meet its charitable objectives, which are to fund
research in the bio-medical field. Venture capital would provide capital
growth.
Second, a portion of the venture capital funds might be invested in start-up
bio-technology companies which commercially exploit scientific research.
This would be consistent with the charity's mission, its advisers believe.
The Trust has professional advisers on investments and risks would be
reduced by diversifying them.
</TEXT>
<XX>
