<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUN 94 / Government welcomes reform plan for universities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A package of radical reforms put forward yesterday by university managers to
ensure that quality does not suffer in the wake of university expansion was
welcomed by the government.
Mr Tim Boswell, higher education minister, said he would take 'very
seriously' the proposals for students to be given vouchers to pay for
education wherever they wished and for universities to be paid according to
units of education they provided to students.
Other recommendations on the agenda are a new vocational 'associate degree',
which could be a stepping stone to a full honours degree, and a national
system of academic credits. This would be transferable from one university
to another, and backed by a uniform national credit 'transcript', in which
standardised details of students' performance would be entered regularly.
The reforms have been proposed by the Higher Education Quality Council, a
group set up by university vice-chancellors with government backing. It said
they were essential if the UK higher education system was to adapt to modern
needs.
Over the past five years, the proportion of 18-year-olds going to university
has doubled, while the number of mature students has also increased.
Without reform, the system could not accommodate students taking career
breaks or combining a career with their degree, the council said.
Professor Peter Toyne, vice-chancellor of Liverpool John Moores University
and chairman of the council's credit and access group, said: 'We are at an
important point in history where we are struggling to keep a system afloat
which is based on past assumptions. If it's going to go further forward,
reform has got to be radical.'
Mr Boswell said the plan for transferable academic credits was in line with
the government's higher education charter. He promised that both the
government and the higher education funding councils would take the funding
proposals 'very seriously'.
He also ordered a report from the Higher Education Quality Council into
growing unease that franchising arrangements used by universities to allow
foreign colleges to award their degrees might have diluted standards.
Mr Boswell said: 'There must be no reduction in standards.'
The council will consult universities and employers on the report until
September 30 this year, with a further report due by the end of the year.
Education funds proposals break with tradition, Page 16
</TEXT>
