<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUN 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Those of us who did not see An Evening With Gary Lineker on stage but did
see BBC1's comedy drama 'Fair Game' on television on Saturday will be
interested to discover how far the BBC production resembles its better known
predecessor when ITV screen their television version tonight (8.30). Both
dramas plait together the twin strands of World Cup football and the
emotional/sexual relationships of a band of onlookers. BBC2 shows the final
episode in Quantum Leap, part of a rich seam of American fantasy which gives
the lie to the common claim that American television only makes crime
series. The central character in Quantum Leap is Sam Beckett who travels
through time, becoming a different person in each episode (9.00). Little
Napoleons sounded like yet another of Channel 4's misconceived series aiming
for something multiracial but merely achieving separatism. However, in the
opening episode Saeed Jaffrey and Norman Beaton were so good as competitive
solicitors who both become councillors that you could forget the race
element altogether (10.00).
