<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUN 94 / Mercury mobile business tariff cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mercury One-2-One, the mobile-phone operator in the London region, yesterday
announced a sharp cut in its business tariff. The move comes a week after
Vodafone, the largest cellular operator, said that tariffs would be
unchanged for the rest of the year.
One-2-One will cut its business tariff from 16p a minute to 14p next week
and its monthly subscription from Pounds 20 to Pounds 17.50.
Business subscribers will be able to make international calls at rates
cheaper than BT's standard tariffs for an extra fee of Pounds 3 a month. For
an extra Pounds 10 they will be able to make local calls without charge on
weekday nights and at weekends.
The move will put pressure on Vodafone and Cellnet, the second-largest
operator, to cut their tariffs, although both operators said their networks
did not need to be price competitive with One-2-One because they offered
national coverage.
The changes pitch One-2-One's tariffs far below those of its larger rivals,
which charge a monthly rental of Pounds 25 and a peak rate tariff of 25p a
minute - reduced to Pounds 20 and 20p respectively on a tariff available in
the London region.
The past year has seen mobile phone tariffs fall by as much as a third, with
two new networks - One-2-One and Orange, operated by Hutchison Microtel -
launched in the past eight months. One-2-One has gained nearly 100,000
subscribers in the London region since September.
Mr Kevin Langford, mobile-cellular analyst at Fleming Securities, said
One-2-One's price cuts appeared to be aimed at shifting business customers
from its residential tariff - which offers no-charge local calls on weekdays
after 7pm and at weekends - and to forestalling competition from Orange,
whose tariffs are particularly attractive to high-usage business customers.
Its network is more extensive than One-2-One's and will be expanded faster.
Mr Richard Goswell, One-2-One managing director, said he did not rule out
raising tariffs again as the network expanded.
The cheapest handset for One-2-One's network retails for Pounds 199, which
is significantly more expensive than those for the analogue networks of the
larger operators.
The UK has nearly 2.5m cellular mobile subscribers, more per capita than
most of the rest of the EU but behind the US and Scandinavia.
Orange claims 30 per cent of subscribers in the London region. Vodafone and
Cellnet, which launched their networks in the mid 1980s, both have more than
1m subscribers.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Mercury Communications.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P4812 Radiotelephone Communications.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
