<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUN 94 / European Elections: Hume slashes Paisley majority
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The three sitting MEPs representing the three main strands of political
opinion in Northern Ireland have all been returned.
The Rev Ian Paisley of the hard-line Democratic Unionist party again topped
the poll, taking 29 per cent, or 163,246 of the total vote of 559,864.
However, his majority of about 14,000 in the 1989 election was reduced to
only 1,250 over Mr John Hume, leader of the mainly nationalist Social
Democratic and Labour party, who has taken the second of the seats in the
three-seat Northern Ireland constituency.
The third seat has been taken by Mr Jim Nicholson, of the Ulster Unionist
party, with 133,459 votes, or 24 per cent.
The province is unique in the UK's polling system in having the only
multi-seat constituency and the only one to use proportional representation
and the single transferable vote system.
There was a 49.4 per cent turnout, half a percen-tage point higher than in
1989.
Significantly, Mr Hume and Mr Nicholson, considered to represent moderate
viewpoints of nationalism and unionism respectively, have both made modest
but notable advances in the level of their support, while that of the
extremes has remained static.
Support for Mr Hume has gone up by 4 percentage points to 29 per cent of the
vote, and that for Mr Nicholson has advanced by 2 percentage points to 24
per cent.
Mr Paisley, who chose to run his campaign as a referendum on the Downing
Street declaration, calling on unionist opponents of the declaration to vote
for the Democratic Unionist party, has seen his overall share of the vote
slip marginally - by 1 percentage point.
Nonetheless, he claimed yesterday that he had achieved what he set out to
do, and has requested an urgent meeting with Mr John Major, the prime
minister.
Sinn Fein, the political wing of the IRA, has seen its support advance by 1
percentage point to 10 per cent, after a significant effort to get all its
supporters out to vote.
The result will give a measure of encouragement to ministers of the British
and Irish governments, who are due to meet in Dublin this Friday to discuss
their next steps in the Northern Ireland peace process, which had been put
on hold until after the elections.
The two governments say that work on a joint 'framework document', which
will propose a series of new political structures for Northern Ireland, is
well advanced.
It is intended that this document will provide the focus for renewed
round-table talks, although the Democratic Unionist party has emphasised it
has no intention of returning to the table unless the Downing Street
declaration is repudiated by the British government.
</TEXT>
