<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUN 94 / Edmonds says unions facing cash collapse: GMB leader
forecasts 'gaps in movement'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A number of Britain's trade unions will suffer financial collapse in the
next two years, a senior union leader predicted yesterday.
Addressing the GMB general union conference in Blackpool, Mr John Edmonds,
general secretary, forecast 'a number of gaps in our trade union movement,
gaps that we and the other survivors must fill'.
Although Mr Edmonds did not mention any union, it is believed he was
thinking among others of Ucatt, the construction union which has severe
financial problems and is in merger talks with the TGWU general union.
The GMB intends to launch a recruitment drive across the labour market and
plans to establish a stronger presence in areas where it has previously been
weak.
Mr Edmonds' self-confidence has been strengthened by the results of his
union's check-off campaign.
The GMB has increased membership as a result of persuading workers to have
their subscriptions to the union deducted by their employers. 'The check-off
campaign has tested the sinews of every union; It has been the survival of
the fittest,' said Mr Edmonds. 'Not every union is doing as well as the
GMB.'
The GMB's exploratory merger talks with the TGWU have not made any progress
over the past 12 months, but Mr Edmonds made clear yesterday that his union
would develop on its own 'a new concept of trade unionism among a fragmented
and vulnerable workforce'.
He said the European Union's social legislation and the return of a Labour
government at the next general election would win 'better trade union rights
in Britain' and this would help the unions to recruit among workers in
secure jobs in the manufacturing sector. But this would 'not be enough any
more' to win support for trade unionism in small workplaces 'where
collective bargaining is some distant dream,' he added.
Recruiting in the non-unionised sector of the labour market was 'the dilemma
we must resolve before this decade is over,' Mr Edmonds said.
'We must go back to our roots' and 're-invent community unionism with the
local trading office as the centre of a network providing solidarity and
mutual support,' he told delegates.
Mr Edmonds added that 'new solidarity based on the local community' would
have 'to replace the natural solidarity of the large site.'
</TEXT>
