<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUN 94 / Minister promises protection for rural post offices in
sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A regulatory framework to ensure the survival of rural post offices would
form part of any privatisation package introduced by the government, the
House of Lords was told yesterday.
Lord Strathclyde, trade and industry minister, assured peers who expressed
concern about the effect of privatisation on rural communities that they
would find a 'great deal of comfort' when the promised consultative green
paper was published. He said the document would be published soon.
Lord Strathclyde said: 'In the same way that we protected rural telephone
boxes when it came to privatisation of BT, there's absolutely no reason why
we should not do the same thing for rural post offices.'
He refused to comment when pressed to explain why, if the Post Office's
counters business could be accorded greater commercial freedom while
remaining in the public sector, the same approach could not be adopted in
the case of the Royal Mail.
Lord Strathclyde reaffirmed, however, that the maintenance of a uniform
postal rate, a universal service, and a nationwide network of services, was
'non-negotiable'.
Lord Clinton-Davis, a Labour spokesman, said that public opposition to the
privatisation of the Post Office had contributed to the government's dismal
showing in the European elections and last week's crop of by-elections for
seats in the House of Commons.
He noted with satisfaction that the government was paying a very high price
at the polls for such acts of 'political lunacy'.
Lord Strathclyde insisted that the privatisation programme had proved
successful, and added: 'Labour policies would have provided no benefit, and
substantial costs.'
</TEXT>
