<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUN 94 / Beckett speech received without great enthusiasm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The speech from Mrs Margaret Beckett, Labour's acting leader, was the
longest and dullest of the three, and had more to offer the party's
traditionalists than its modernisers, David Goodhart writes.
Speaking before the other two candidates, in the slot that would have been
filled by John Smith, Mrs Beckett was received attentively but without great
enthusiasm.
Her only direct appeal to the delegates to vote for her took the form of a
joke: 'I will make only one point in my own cause. After the next general
election we could look forward to hearing militant Tories chanting 'Maggie
Maggie Maggie - out out out]' '
After a triumphant assessment of the European election results - 'a turning
point in British history' - Mrs Beckett talked of the need for a better
balance between individual and community, but also had some meat for the
left, stressing the importance of the links between unions and the party.
'Our relationship brings reality to what can otherwise become the unreal
world of politics. And it is vital to the political problems that we as a
party must address,' she said.
She also talked of government taking a lead in industries of the future.
Modernisers would have been happier with her comments on the need to
modernise the welfare state.
</TEXT>
