<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JUN 94 / World Trade News: Talks on trade 'not complete'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The achievement of the Uruguay Round of global trade talks 'is still far
from complete' and European Union leaders must treat its ratification with
urgency, Mr Peter Sutherland, director-general of the General Agreement on
Trade and Tariffs, said in Dublin yesterday.
Mr Sutherland told a meeting of the EU economic and social committee that
Europe had 'a responsibility to give leadership on ratification' by the 125
states that signed the Gatt agreements in Marrakesh in April.
The World Trade Organisation (WTO) which will replace Gatt, is due to be
established by January 1, 1995 under the auspices of the Uruguay Round
agreement.
It will have stronger powers than Gatt to enforce the liberalised trade
arrangements which now extend to agri-culture, services, textiles and
intellectual property rights.
The Uruguay Round agreements 'will reward those who have embraced
competition as an ally with improved opportunities to compete in the
fastest-growing markets in the world - the upper-income developing
countries'.
</TEXT>
