<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUN 94 / European Elections: Bad turnout in Britain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUTLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This has been an exciting and unexpected night, David Butler writes. Britain
stays at the the bottom of the turnout league - though the 33 per cent
participation, a repeat of 1989, was matched this time by the Netherlands.
If the Liberal Democrats now appear a regional party confined to the
south-west, the Conservatives are now a party of the non-London south.
Eight recounts make a record - there have never been anything like so many
in a Euro election.
The Conservative wipe-out suggested by the Eastleigh by-election result has
not materialised, but with 27 per cent of the vote the Tories have polled 8
per cent below their previous lowest national vote this century. They have
lost to Labour every seat that they could have lost to them - and for Labour
to take Suffolk and push the Conservatives to a recount in Sussex South and
Crawley is beyond any expectation.
The Tories' comfort lies in the failure of the Liberal Democrats to break
through. Victories in the Cotswolds, in Oxfordshire and Wiltshire must
delight them.
The Conservatives have been lucky in several marginal seats but it is still
startling that with 27 per cent of the vote they are expected to get only 18
of the 87 UK seats. The electoral system, which has been so kind at
Westminster, has turned against them with a vengeance.
Labour has eliminated every Conservative north of a line from Colchester to
the Severn (except for North Yorkshire). The swing nationally was about 14
per cent, but in the London area it was 16 per cent.
David Butler is a fellow of Nuffield College, Oxford.
</TEXT>
