<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUN 94 / European Elections: Beckett jubilant at string of victories
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Senior Labour politicians claimed last night that their European election
gains had exceeded the party's wildest expectations and amounted to a
crushing defeat for the Conservatives.
However, Tory party managers, while acknowledging that they had endured
heavy losses, were relieved that their party had not suffered the electoral
'meltdown' that was feared.
Instead, Labour and Tory politicians were quick to claim that the Liberal
Democrats had been the main losers on the night, amid signs that Mr Paddy
Ashdown's party would not gain many of its target seats.
Mrs Margaret Beckett, the acting Labour leader, described her party's gains
as 'absolutely wonderful'. Throughout the campaign, Labour had feared that
the party would find it hard to improve on its performance in the last
European elections. But, as a string of Labour victories was announced, Mrs
Beckett said that the Conservatives had been 'overtaken by a political
earthquake'.
She said of the Tory leadership: 'In 1989 they thought they were down to
their irreducible minimum, down to their core vote. Now we are eating into
that core vote.'
Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, said the Tories had endured their
worst result for 100 years. 'Labour has broken through in areas like Essex
and Norfolk which we haven't won since 1945 and 1966. The Conservative
government is living on borrowed time. The betrayals have now caught up with
them.'
Mrs Pauline Green, the leader of the Labour group in the European
parliament, said that Tory divisions over Europe had been the main reason
for the party's defeat. 'This election has been about the Europe people want
to see,' she said. 'The Tories are clearly riven top-to-bottom over Europe
while the Labour party is united in its approach.'
The mood at Conservative Central Office was gloomy, but tinged with relief
that the number of Tory seats would end up in double figures.
Sir Norman Fowler, the Conservative party chairman, regretted that his party
had lost so many seats, but said that it had performed much better than most
forecasters thought.
He went on to claim that yesterday's defeat could even be the low point in
the party's recent run of ill fortune. 'It marks what could be the start of
recovery as far as the Conservative party is concerned,' he said.
According to Mr David Hunt, the employment secretary, the party could still
make a comeback at the next election 'provided we listen to the message of
the voters in this election'.
However, some of the sitting Tory MEPs who lost their seats last night could
not refrain from criticising the government for helping to bring about their
defeats.
After losing his London North West seat, Lord Bethell, the longest-serving
English MEP to stand in the election, said that the Tory party 'should pull
its socks up'.
He said: 'There was a feeling amongst the people that they wanted to punish
the government, give it a kick, and I'm one of the victims.'
Mrs Teresa Gorman was one of a number of anti-European Tory MPs to claim
that the low turnout underlined that people wanted Britain to reduce its
commitments in Europe.
'Seventy per cent of the British people have turned their backs on Europe,
and that is the most important thing in this election,' she said.
The Liberal Democrats were initially jubilant at winning their first seat.
But Mrs Beckett claimed that the Liberal Democrats' performance showed they
were not a viable alternative to Labour as an opposition party.
'People are seeing right across Britain that if they want to get rid of this
government they have to go for a real alternative and that is Labour.'
</TEXT>
