<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUN 94 / European Elections: Labour finds way round the pickets -
Campaign Diary
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Labour is unrepentant about barring party officials, MPs and candidates from
the BBC during the strike-hit election coverage on Thursday. The decision,
taken by acting leader Margaret Beckett, left BBC journalists trying to put
the Labour viewpoint during studio discussions.
A few made it on to the screens anyway - taking part in artificial press
conferences attended only by BBC journalists. 'OK, it was a device, but it
meant we didn't break the rules,' said an official.
                         *      *      *
Tony Blair's success in collecting the nominations of 136 Labour MPs caused
some confusion among the Sunday newspapers, which were unsure how many
Labour MPs there are, and how many sit in the shadow cabinet.
The papers split equally between 268 and 269 MPs, but The Observer plumped
for 21 shadow ministers, and The Independent for 19.
In fact, there are 270 Labour MPs, with one Labour-held seat vacant
following the death of John Smith. Two MPs - speaker Betty Boothroyd and
deputy speaker Geoffrey Lofthouse - do not vote on party matters, leaving
268 free to nominate candidates.
There are 18 elected members of the shadow cabinet, plus the leader and
deputy leader, the chief whip, the leader and chief whip in the Lords -
although neither peer has an automatic vote - and the party chairman if he
is not already a member. That makes a potential total of 24.
Since the leader's seat is vacant, and David Blunkett, the party chairman,
sits as an elected member, the correct total is 22. But it falls to 20 if
the two peers are excluded, or 19 if you exclude Blunkett, who has said he
will take no part in the election to protect the neutrality of the chair.
Why is nothing ever easy in the Labour party?
Alec Kellaway, the Newham Liberal Democrat candidate who defected to Labour
a day before last week's by-election, will forever be known at Westminster
as Which Way Kellaway. But he has also made a lasting contribution to the
political argot: Kellaway - one who flits from from party to party, usually
embarrassing both.
                         *      *      *
Lots of politicians have problems with grammar. Margaret Thatcher, who had a
habit of omitting definite and indefinite articles, was a particular
offender. But John Prescott takes the biscuit, as anyone who heard his
virtually incomprehensible speech on voting systems at last year's Labour
conference will know.
Reporters usually clean up Prescott's prose, as they did Thatcher's. But as
the Labour leadership campaign gets under way, here is a sample of unedited
Prescott talking during a BBC interview yesterday about the Beveridge
Commission's 1944 definition of full employment as an unemployment rate of
2.5 per cent of the workforce: 'Two and a half million is the level that is
set by the government on claimants. There is something like about 4 to 5m
people available for work according to the ILO in Britain. Because we fiddle
the figures we don't know. So if you ask me about the 2 1/2 per cent, 2 1/2
per cent of 2 1/2 m is a different kind of definition to that of 4 or 5m.'
I don't know what it means either. Prescott added: 'There is no intelligent
debate about these matters. I want to re-introduce intelligent debate.'
                         *      *      *
The City seems unsure whether to take the European elections seriously. Some
currency and bond dealers remember with trepidation the millions of pounds
made and lost after the Danish 'No' to the Maastricht treaty in June 1992,
and the narrow French 'Yes' a few months later.
Steve Hannah, head of research at Japanese investment bank IBJ
International, points to the increased power of the European parliament, the
implications of a poor showing for interest rates and the Tory leadership.
But others think the City will greet the results with a yawn. David Cocker,
chief economist at Chemical Bank, said: 'The apathetic attitude of the
British electorate is likely to be reflected in the apathetic response of
the markets.'
</TEXT>
