<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUN 94 / European Elections: Computer leaves Ashdown smiling through
gritted teeth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
At the Liberal Democrats' Westminster headquarters in Cowley Street a huge
crowd of mainly young party activists had gathered from early yesterday
evening for what they expected would be a celebration over bottles of wine
and Coca-Cola.
But as the evening wore on - showing the party failing to make the big gains
in the south that some opinion polls had predicted - the mood became more
subdued.
The switch from euphoria to silence had its most dramatic and poignant
moment just after midnight. The live television coverage reported a Liberal
Democrat gain in Surrey. A huge cheer broke out and Mr Paddy Ashdown and his
campaign manager Mr Matthew Taylor embraced in front of the cameras.
Then while Mr Ashdown was in full flow, expressing his delight at the result
and predicting the beginning of the end of a long struggle to wrench control
of the south from the Conservative party, the television commentator
corrected the result to a Conservative win, and apologised for a computer
error.
With that announcement Cowley Street fell temporarily silent and Mr Ashdown,
visibly shaken, walked from the room, leaving Mr Taylor to rationalise the
result.
Mr Taylor blamed Labour for allowing Mr Major to do better than expected
against the Liberal Democrats. 'What we are seeing is the Labour party doing
well enough in the south and south-west at our expense and making it
possible for the Conservatives to hang on. John Major may well end up
thanking the Labour party for allowing him to hang on to his job for another
term and saving his bacon.'
By 12.45am some spirits at Liberal Democrat headquarters were again elated
by the news that after their second gain there were two further seats where
recounts were taking place.
Mr Ashdown was back in front of the television cameras wearing a huge grin.
He predicted that the party would still emerge from the night better than
anyone could have predicted a year ago. Even after the earlier
disappointment of Surrey, Liberal Democrat activists took heart from the
election of their first Euro MP. One party worker, Mr David Charlesworth,
said: 'For us to get even one Euro MP is a breakthrough. Any more will be
the cream on top of the cake.' Another worker, Mr David Cloke, said: 'Any
gain is good news for us and we'll be happy if we end up with two.'
</TEXT>
