<PROFILE>_AN-EFND1AH3FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940613
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUN 94 / European Elections: Champagne corks pop in Walworth Rd
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There was elation at Labour's headquarters in London's Walworth Road early
this morning. Volunteers uncorked champagne bottles as they analysed the
results.
Mr Larry Whitty, general secretary, said the results showed Labour doing
'substantially better than any of us expected'. Mr Whitty revealed that the
party's eve-of-poll internal soundings had been showing Labour gaining a
maximum of 50 to 55 seats. By early morning it was looking as if the party
would go beyond 60.
Mr Whitty had more than that to celebrate. He pointed to Labour victories
right across the country, a virtual 'wipeout' of the Tory vote in London -
and perhaps the most applauded result in the headquarters all evening - the
capture of Essex Man deep in the Tory heartlands.
Among those milling around Walworth Road was the shadow secretary to the
Treasury, Ms Harriet Harman, anxious to make sure that her comments for the
evening would be overheard by the Financial Times: 'What the people of Essex
have said is that they don't believe that the Tories represent the party of
low tax any more. Now Essex Man and Woman have turned to Labour.'
Among the many results striking a particularly poignant note for the
gathered party activists was the election of Mr Neil Kinnock's wife Glenys
as a Euro MP. Her celebration speech was a striking contrast to the Glenys
Kinnock who stood outside the same building during the last general election
tearfully recording the national humiliation of her husband.
It was left to Mr Frank Dobson, transport spokesman, to contribute his joke
for the evening amidst the euphoria. Gleefully watching the Conservative
rout on the television, Mr Dobson said: 'It is a real record-breaking night
for John Major. In fact it is like Brian Lara in reverse - he is breaking so
many records.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8651 Political Organizations.
</IN>
<XX>
