<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUN 94 / Company News (This Week): Recovery may prove a moving
experience - NFC
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
NFC's performance is viewed as a bellwether indicator of economic activity,
so the transport and logistics group's interim results due out on Wednesday
will be carefully scrutinised.
In March the group, which reports its results on a quarterly basis, reported
an 11 per cent increase in underlying growth. At that stage the company,
which derives around two thirds of its revenues from the UK, said the
domestic economic recovery remained variable, and noted there were no signs
of recovery in continental Europe.
The second quarter is traditionally the weakest for NFC and year-on-year
comparisons this time around will be particularly onerous because the
year-ago figures were flattered by the Pounds 50m profit on the sale of the
group's waste management arm.
Reflecting this, first half pre-tax profits on an FRS3 basis are likely to
fall from Pounds 86.6m to Pounds 53m. However they should show healthy
growth from Pounds 37.5m to about Pounds 49m on a normalised basis as the
recovery in the US and UK economies begins to pull more consumer goods
through the distribution pipeline serviced by NFC's logistic operations.
Meanwhile the upturn in the housing markets should help Pickfords moving
services but investors will also be looking for further clarification on the
future of Lynx, the loss-making parcels business.
Earnings growth will continue to be held back by the dilutive effects of the
Pounds 263m rights issue completed in January which has nevertheless removed
balance sheet pressures and provided additional flexibility to expand the
distribution and removal businesses internationally.
NFC has already used some of the resulting Pounds 89.4m net cash to fund a
handful of modest-sized acquisitions including several overseas.
</TEXT>
