<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUN 94 / Brussels rethink over steel plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS and LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The European Commission will this week reconsider its rescue plan for the
steel industry amid renewed warnings from Mr Karel Van Miert, European Union
competition commissioner, that he will walk away from it unless he wins
support for a flexible interpretation of rules on state aid.
Mr Van Miert's stand puts him on a collision course with Sir Leon Brittan,
chief EU trade negotiator. Sir Leon is unhappy about the planned grant of
Ecu415m (Pounds 319.55m) in Italian state aid in exchange for the closure of
steelmaking in Brescia, northern Italy. Sir Leon fears that this would
undermine efforts to reach a steel agreement with the US.
Mr Van Miert said the Brescia cuts were crucial for the Commission to reach
its target of reducing steelmaking capacity in the EU by 19m tonnes by
September. Some bending of the rules was necessary if the targets were to be
met, he added.
In Brussels, Mr Van Miert's allies hope Sir Leon will soften his position to
win the backing of the Italian government for his bid to succeed Mr Jacques
Delors as president of the European Commission. A spokesman for Sir Leon
said the two issues were separate. Mr Van Miert's decision to distance
himself from the steel rescue plan means that the slim chances of a revival
lie with Germany's Mr Martin Bangemann, EU industry commissioner.
Mr Bangemann, co-architect of the plan, wants a generous interpretation of
the rules to take account of the complicated cross-ownership of the Brescia
mini-mills. The web of company shareholdings means not all companies linked
to steelmaking would close, raising the legal question of whether state aid
can be used for 'partial closures'.
Last month, Mr Van Miert suffered a defeat after Sir Leon argued in favour
of a rigorous interpretation of the steel code on state subsidies.
Mr Van Miert said he was relaxed about a possible collapse of the steel
plan.
'I was simply trying to do what I had been asked, but if the conclusion is
we can't go ahead, that is no problem,' he said.
Mr Van Miert said he had opposed proposals to adopt an interventionist steel
policy based on production quotas that would have resulted only in freezing
capacity. German steel producers are believed to have favoured such a
'crisis cartel' approach.
Van Miert interview, Page 2 See Lex
</TEXT>
