<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUN 94 / Brussels to rethink planto rescue steel industry: Van Miert
seeks more flexibility on state aid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS and LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The European Commission will this week reconsider its rescue plan for the
steel industry amid renewed warnings from Mr Karel Van Miert, European Union
competition commissioner, that he will walk away from it unless he wins
support for a flexible interpretation of rules on state aid.
Mr Van Miert's stand puts him on a collision course with Sir Leon Brittan,
chief EU trade negotiator. Sir Leon is unhappy about the planned grant of
Ecu415m (Pounds 319.55m) in Italian state aid in exchange for the closure of
steelmaking in Brescia, northern Italy. Sir Leon fears that this would
undermine efforts to reach a steel agreement with the US.
In an interview with the Financial Times, Mr Van Miert said the Brescia cuts
were crucial for the Commission reaching its target of cutting steelmaking
capacity in the EU by a total 19m tonnes by September. Some bending of the
rules was necessary if the targets were to be met, he added.
In Brussels, Mr Van Miert's allies are betting that Sir Leon will soften his
position in order to win the backing of the Italian government for his bid
to succeed Mr Jacques Delors as the next president of the European
Commission. A spokesman for Sir Leon said the two issues were entirely
separate.
Mr Van Miert's decision to distance himself from the steel rescue plan means
that the slim chances of a revival lie with Germany's Mr Martin Bangemann,
EU industry commissioner.
Mr Bangemann, co-architect of the plan, wants a generous inter pretation of
the rules to take account of the complicated cross-ownership of the Brescia
mini-mills. The web of company shareholdings means that not all companies
linked to steelmaking would shut down, raising the legal question of whether
state aid could be used for 'partial closures'.
Last month, Mr Van Miert suffered a defeat after Sir Leon argued in favour
of a rigorous interpretation of the steel code on state subsidies.
Mr Van Miert said he was relaxed about a possible collapse of the steel
plan.
'I was simply trying to do what I had been asked, but if the conclusion is
we can't go ahead, that is no problem,' he said. He repeated warnings that
the EU would open proceedings against Italian steel industry aids as well as
a case against Luxembourg steel production.
Mr Van Miert noted that he had opposed proposals to adopt an interventionist
steel policy based on production quotas that would have only resulted in
freezing capacity. German steel producers are believed to have favoured such
a 'crisis cartel' approach.
Instead, Mr Van Miert and Mr Bangemann had opted for the more flexible
approach, combining support measures in exchange for capacity cuts.
Unless the deadlock can be resolved, the Commission will put an end in
September to the flanking financial aid measures currently available for the
decommissioning of capacity.
Van Miert interview, Page 2 Usinor to raise Ilva steels bid, Page 3 See Lex
</TEXT>
